      "author_association": "NONE",
      "body": "Intolerance of \"outdated\" versions means that you have to be 100% right, 100% of the time AND all of your dependencies have to right 100% of the time.  If I try `npx create-react-app@3.0.1 my-app` you get this problem `This is likely because you're using an outdated version`.\r\n\r\nIn 3.1.0, SASS module composition is broken (but not in 3.0.1).  But if you try to work around this breakage by specifying the @3.0.1 you get the above message and a mostly empty project directory.  This is not all that useful.  This happens even if you specify `--template=typescript`.\r\n\r\n```\r\nnpx create-react-app@3.0.1 --template=typescript zee\r\n```\r\n\r\nI understand that to cut down on support this might seem like the right path, but I think it basically means that trying to spin up a react project now is even more of a crapshoot than it has been in the past since random things will still be broken, but rolling back to a good working version will no longer work.  \r\n\r\nI thought the aim of this project was to make it easier to get started, but this path is going to lead to more headaches, not less.\r\n\r\nRight now my workaround is create a busted project using the head branch, then create a usable project using @3.0.1, then copying over the missing pieces from the busted project so that in the end I can have a working project that doesn't break sass module based imports.  All of this could be resolved by allowing the user to rollback using the @ mechanism in npx.\r\n\r\n### Describe the solution you'd like\r\n\r\nDon't take away the templates just because the latest version of create-react-app wasn't used.\r\n\r\n### Describe alternatives you've considered\r\n\r\nSee my workarounds above.\r\n\r\n### Additional context\r\n\r\nI'm trying to repair an existing CRA app that has drifted too far in versions from anything that remotely seems to allow things to work.  I'm trying to build a baseline I can use to build, test, storybook this project and feel that my head is bruised from banging into your walls."
